[normal]8.[bold]              [bold]About the Road Safety Markings Association (RSMA)[bold]&#xa0;[bold]8.1[bold]              
[normal]RSMA is the largest specialist trade 
[normal]association in the highways sector, representing more than 90 per cent of the sector by volume it has a total of 95 member companies all of which carry relevant quality assurance as a requirement of membership
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.2[bold]              
[normal]The RSMA’s activities emphasise quality,
[normal] health &amp; safety and training and it has invested substantially in these areas over the past decade, in order to help highways companies and organisations to drive up sector standards and deliver higher quality in a safer manner.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] It has a clear focus on s
[normal]etting standards for its members.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.3[bold]              
[normal]The association has developed a large
[normal] NVQ
[normal] Assessment Centre, qualifying in excess of 800 road marking operatives and has been the first
[normal] organisation
[normal] to introduce specialist apprenticeships in the highways sector.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The
[normal] centre delivers or facilitates delivery of a wide range of
[normal] NVQ
[normal] and training solutions for roadmarking companies.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] As a result, 90 per cent of the operative workforce is qualified, and there is a clear career structure now in place for the industry for bot
[normal]h management and operatives.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.[bold]4[bold]              
[normal]RSMA is the only organisation which carries out a full condition survey of the UK road markings and has been carrying it out 
[normal]at least 
[normal]every two years since 2001.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.5[bold]              
[normal]The RSMA has, as an industry body,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]imposed standards on
[normal] its sector and pushed up quality,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]improved training and defined
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]specific health and safety best practice for the sector moving the sector away from inadequate and often inaccurate blanket health and safety policies.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]October 2013
[normal]&#xa0;
